Looks as if there is some clustering in the data. Doesnt look like theres a major difference in shopping score by gender.

customers_subset <- mall_customers %>% 
  select(annual_income_k, spending_score_1_100)

# Scaling so that both variables can be measured 
customers_scale <- customers_subset %>% 
  mutate_all(scale)
fviz_nbclust(customers_scale,
             kmeans,
             method = "silhouette",
             nstart = 25)

fviz_nbclust(customers_scale,
             kmeans,
             method = "gap_stat",
             nstart = 25) # No, don't like
Clustering k = 1,2,..., K.max (= 10): .. done

.................................................. 50 
.................................................. 100

5 clusters looks like a good fit

customer_clusters %>% 
  unnest(augmented) %>% 
  filter(k == 5) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(annual_income_k, spending_score_1_100, colour = .cluster, label = customer_id)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(hjust = 0, vjust = -0.5, size = 3)

Clustering seems a good fit for the data. When I initially explored the data I thought 5 clusters would be suitable.

Those with a middling income also seem to have a middling spending score (densly packed too). Those on a lower or higher annual income (>50<) seem to be split into 2 roughly equal groups. One with a low spending score and the other with a high spending score.
